text: Isolation of the lysolipin gene cluster of Streptomyces tendae Tü 4042 Patricio Lopez a,1, Andreas Hornung b,1, Katrin Welzel b, Claudia Unsin a, Wolfgang Wohlleben a, Tilmann Weber a,⁎,2, Stefan Pelzer b,2 a Mikrobiologie/Biotechnologie, Interfakultäres Institut für Mikrobiologie und Infektionsmedizin, Eberhard-Karls-Universität Tübingen, Auf der Morgenstelle 28, 72076 Tübingen, Germany b MerLion Pharmaceuticals GmbH, Robert-Rössle-Str. 10, 13125 Berlin, Germany Article history: Received 2 December 2009 Received in revised form 31 March 2010 Accepted 31 March 2010 Available online 25 April 2010 Keywords: Antibiotics Streptomyces Polyketide Lysolipin Xanthone Antibiotic PKS The occurrence of multidrug-resistant pathogens is a serious and constantly growing threat in human medicine (Nathan, 2004). To address this severe problem, new and more sophisticated approaches are needed to develop novel antimicrobials for clinical use. Alterations to these molecules can be achieved by chemical derivatizations (Khosla and Tang, 2005) or combinatorial biosynthesis (Floss, 2006; Rodriguez and McDaniel, 2001). Polyketides are an important family of compounds, comprising over 10,000 members. Many polyketides are commercially used as antibiotics (e.g., tetracyclines and erythro- mycin), immunosuppressants (FK506), anticancer substances (doxo- rubicin), and antifungals (nystatin). Streptomyces tendae Tü 4042 produces the aromatic polyketide antibiotic lysolipin. Lysolipin has strong antibacterial activity against a variety of multidrug-resistant pathogens. The complete lysolipin biosynthetic gene cluster was isolated and fully sequenced. Within a 42-kb genomic region, 42 genes were identiﬁed that code for a type II polyketide synthase (llpF, E, and D), cyclases (llpCI–CIII), methyltransferases (llpMI–MVI), a halogenase (llpH), an amidotransferase (llpA), a ferredoxin (llpK), a transporter (llpN) and regulatory proteins (llpRI–RV). In addition, 15 genes encoding enzymes involved in redox modiﬁcations of the polyketide precursor molecule (llpOI–OVIII, ZI–ZIV, U, L, and S) were present in the lysolipin biosynthetic gene cluster. With this high number of oxidoreductases, lysolipin is among the most highly modiﬁed aromatic polyketides known to date. The heterologous expression of the cluster in Streptomyces albus led to lysolipin production with a yield comparable to that of wild-type, indicating that all biosynthetic genes were successfully cloned. 2009). Modular polyketide synthase (PKS) enzymes (type I) resemble vertebrate fatty acid synthases (FAS), while PKS involved in the synthesis of aromatic compounds resemble bacterial or plant FAS. These type II PKS consist of a set of core enzymes called the “minimal PKS,” consisting of ketosynthase α, (KSα), ketosynthase β/chain- length factor (KSβ/CLF), and acyl carrier protein (ACP). The minimal PKS synthesizes a polyketide precursor, which is subsequently cyclized (for reviews, see Das and Khosla, 2009; Hertweck et al., 2007). This precursor ﬁnally is modiﬁed by tailoring enzymes, which can introduce, for example, oxygenations, halogenations, methyla- tions, glycosylations, and structural rearrangements. These tailoring steps have important effects on the physicochemical properties and biological activity of the resulting molecule. Within these diverse tailoring reactions lies a huge potential for generating new substances with novel, and perhaps improved, properties by combining corresponding enzymes from different biosynthetic pathways (Floss, 2006; Pelzer et al., 2005). The aromatic polyketide lysolipin (Fig. 1) was ﬁrst isolated in 1975 from Streptomyces violaceoniger Tü 96 (Drautz et al., 1975), and later from Streptomyces tendae Tü 4042 (Blum, 1995). It is highly active at very low concentrations (MIC 0.001 µg mL− 1) against a variety of gram-positive bacteria; it also possesses tumorstatic activity (Pultar, 1988). Lysolipin displays a very high afﬁnity for lipids. Drautz et al. (1975) suggested that its mode of antibacterial action may be based on an interaction with the C55-lipid carrier bactoprenol, which is involved in cell-wall biosynthesis. The polycyclic and aromatic character of lysolipin implies that lysolipin biosynthesis is based on the type II PKS mechanism. P. Lopez et al. / Gene 461 (2010) 5–14 The 24-carbon polyketide backbone makes lysolipin one of the largest known aromatic polyketides. It has structural similarities to pradimicin, (Oki et al., 1988) griseorhodin (Eckardt et al., 1978; Li and Piel, 2002), rubromycin (Brockmann et al., 1966), fredericamycin (Pandey et al., 1981), benastatin (Aoyagi et al., 1992) and some other large polyketides.

A prominent structural feature of lysolipin is a post-PKS rear- rangement that results in a xanthone. This moiety is rarely observed in bacterial metabolites. Other structural aspects include the presence of a methylenedioxy bridge and a chlorine atom on ring A (Fig. 1). Studies with isotope-labeled precursors revealed incorporation of eleven malonate-derived acetate units. A twelfth malonate unit was found to be completely incorporated into the N-containing heterocy- cle (Bockholt et al., 1994). The presence of nine oxygen-atoms derived from molecular oxygen, four SAM-derived methyl groups, and a SAM- derived methylene bridge led to the hypothesis that a high number of genes encoding oxidoreductive and modifying enzymes must be involved in lysolipin biosynthesis (Bockholt et al., 1994). In this report, we describe the cloning, sequencing, and analysis of the lysolipin-biosynthetic gene cluster. Successful production of lysolipin was observed in a heterologous host, Streptomyces albus, which was transformed with cosmid 4H04 containing the putative biosynthetic gene cluster; this result indicated that all of the genes required for lysolipin synthesis were located within the 42-kb region cloned from S. tendae Tü 4042. 2.1. Bacterial strains and growth conditions

The lysolipin producer S. tendae Tü 4042 was obtained from the “Tübinger Stammsammlung.” Lysolipin production was achieved by inoculating spores in R5 medium (Kieser et al., 2000) or tryptic soy broth (100 mL) for two days. A total of 2–2.5% (v/v) of this preculture was used to inoculate the production medium (SFM; 20% full-fat soybean ﬂour, 20% mannitol, pH 7.5, tap water) or R5. Cultures were grown at 27 °C and 180 rpm in a shaking incubator (Infors Multitron). The earliest detection of lysolipin occurred after two days of growth in the production medium. Due to the stability of lysolipin I, no special point in time had to be monitored for its isolation. S. albus G J1074 (Chater and Wilde, 1980) was used as a host for heterologous expression. The same protocol was used for lysolipin production in S. albus and wild-type S. tendae Tü 4042, with the only difference being the use of R5 instead of SFM as the production medium. The host for the cosmid library was E. coli DH5α (Invitrogen). For triparental intergeneric conjugation experiments, E. coli GM2163 (Palmer and Marinus, 1994), which contained the mobilizing RP4 derivative pUB307 (Bennett et al., 1977), was used. E. coli cultivation was carried out in Luria–Bertani medium supplemented with the appropriate antibiotics at their recommended concentrations (Sam- brook and Russell, 2001). 2.2. Extraction of lysolipin and HPLC-DAD-MS analysis

For lysolipin extraction, the pH of the production culture was adjusted with HCl to 3, the medium extracted twice with ethyl acetate, and the extract was subsequently concentrated in a rotary evaporator. At the low pH used for extraction, lysolipin X is fully converted to lysolipin I. HPLC- DAD-MS analysis was performed on a Agilent 1200 HPLC and a Agilent LC/MSD XTC6300 Ultra Trap mass spectrometer. The samples were analyzed using a gradient (solvent A: 0.1% formic acid in water, solvent B: 0.06% formic acid in acetonitrile; ﬂow rate: 400 µL min− 1; 0–15 min 90% A/10% B to 0% A/100% B, 15–17 min 0% A/100% B, posttime 5 min 10% B). Mass spectra were recorded over the full mass range in positive- and negative ion mode. DNA isolation and manipulation were performed according to standard protocols (Kieser et al., 2000; Sambrook and Russell, 2001). P. Lopez et al. / Gene 461 (2010) 5–14 DNA isolation from agarose gels was performed using a QIAGEN QIAquick Kit or Amersham GFX columns. PCR ampliﬁcations were performed using Taq DNA polymerase (Qiagen). Restriction enzymes were purchased from New England Biolabs, MBI Fermentas and Amersham and used according to the suppliers' recommendations. 2.4. Generation of cosmid library of S. tendae Tü 4042 A genomic library of S. tendae Tü 4042 was generated according to previously described protocols (Beye et al., 1998; Burgtorf et al., 1998). For details on library generation, see Xu et al. (2005). 2.5. Cosmid library screening Hybridizing probes were nonradioactively labeled using the Roche PCR DIG Probe Synthesis Kit. Primers used for probe labeling were synthesized as follows.

Ketosynthase gene probes were generated according to Metsä- Ketelä et al. (1999) using the KS-forward-primer 5′-TSG CST GCT TGG AYG CSA TC-3′ and, KS-reverse-primer 5′-TGG AAN CCG CCG AAB CCG CT-3′. The PCR-program was as follows: 95 °C for 1 min, 30 cycles of 95 °C for 1 min, 72 °C for 2 min, and; 72 °C for 1:30 min, followed by 72 °C for 5 min using an MJ Research PTC 225 thermocycler. The PKS-II amplicons were approximately 600 bp long. Halogenase gene probes were generated according to van Pée and Zehner (van Pee and Zehner, 2003) using the Halo-forward-primer 5′-GCG GCT GCA GST GGD WSA TYC CGY T-3′ and, Halo-reverse-primer 5′-CCS STG GAT CCS CGG GTC SAB GAA GC-3′. The PCR program was as follows: 94 °C for 2 min, 25 cycles of 94 °C for 1 min, 61 °C for 1 min, and 72 °C for 1 min, followed by 72 °C for 10 min using an MJ Research PTC 100 thermo- cycler. Halogenase gene amplicons were approximately 260 bp long. Both fragments were used as DNA probes to screen the colony ﬁlters. Hybridization and detection experiments were performed under standard conditions. The chemiluminescence of hybridizing probes was detected using a FujiFilm FLA-3000 scanner. 2.6. Sequencing and sequence analysis

Shotgun sequencing of the cosmids was performed by GATC Biotech, Konstanz, Germany. Raw sequence data were assembled and ﬁnished using the software pipeline phred/phrap/consed (Ewing et al., 1998; Ewing and Green, 1998; Gordon et al., 1998). In the ﬁrst step, automatic gene ﬁnding was performed using the gene ﬁnder ZCurve (Guo et al., 2003). For ZCurve, a training sequence was needed to be appended to the lysolipin cluster sequence to improve the quality of the ZCurve assignments. Next, the ZCurve gene ﬁnding process was started. Finally, the extender sequence was removed. As the automatic gene-ﬁnding process is error prone, manual control and improvement of gene prediction were necessary and was performed using the frame-plot (Ishikawa and Hotta, 1999) tool provided by the ARTEMIS program (Rutherford et al., 2000). Homologous sequences were identiﬁed using BLAST (Altschul et al., 1990), and protein motifs were identiﬁed with InterProScan (Zdobnov and Apweiler, 2001). 2.7. Triparental intergeneric conjugation

The transfer of cosmids from E. coli DH5α to S. albus was accom- plished by triparental conjugation. E. coli DH5α carrying the cosmids to be transferred and S. albus spores recruited the transfer functions of the IncP-helper plasmid pUB307 (Bennett et al., 1977; Flett et al., 1997), which was provided by E. coli GM2163 (Palmer and Marinus, 1994) as the third strain. Overnight cultures of E. coli GM2163 and DH5α were used in a modiﬁed conjugation protocol according to Kieser et al. (2000). The two E. coli strains and S. albus spores were spread on SFM-plates (20% soybean ﬂour, 20% mannitol, 1.6% agar, 10 mM MgCl2, pH 7.5) for 12 h at 29 °C. After 12 h, the plates were overlaid with 1 mL H2Odeion supplemented with 30 µL of apramycin (50 mg mL− 1, antibiotic for exconjugant selection) and 30 µL of phosphomycin (100 mg mL− 1 for counterselection against E. coli). 2.8. Cloning and expression of llpG

The gene llpG encoding a putative glycosyltransferase was ampliﬁed by PCR using the primers llpG-5′ (5′-CAC CAT ATG CGT GTG CTG TTC AC-3′; NdeI-site) and llpG-3′ (5′-ACA GGA TCC CGC CAC ACA TAG CGA-3′), cloned into vector pJet (Fermentas), sequenced and ﬁnally cloned into the NdeI/BamHI sites of pRM4.3 (Menges et al., 2007). The llpG expression plasmid was introduced into S. albus using standard intergeneric conjugation. For inhibition zone experiments, HA agar plates (plate volume 30 mL; 10 g L− 1 malt extract, 4 g L− 1 yeast extract, 4 g L− 1 glucose, pH 7.3) were overlaid with 108 spores of S. albus in 4 mL Nutrient Broth (Difco) soft agar. Filter discs with were soaked with 10 µL of lysolipin stock solutions (1 mg L− 1 in methanol), air-dried and put on the plates. The diameter of the inhibition zones was measured after three days of growth at 30°C. The sequence of the lysolipin-biosynthetic gene cluster was deposited in the EMBL database under the accession no. EMBL AC: AM492533. 3. Results and discussion 3.1. Identiﬁcation and isolation of the lysolipin-biosynthetic gene cluster A cosmid library of the lysolipin producer S. tendae Tü 4042 was constructed using the integrative cosmid vector pOJ436 (Bierman et al., 1992). Samples were automatically processed in 384-well plates and transferred to high-density clone arrays.

Hybridization probes were generated by PCR labeling using degenerate primers. An internal KSα probe was ampliﬁed using KS- forward and KS-reverse primers (Metsä-Ketelä et al., 1999). Because it was known that many secondary metabolite producers contain several PKS gene clusters (e.g. Bentley et al., 2002; Oliynyk et al., 2007; Omura et al., 2001; Weber et al., 2003), a second screening probe was required to speciﬁcally identify the lysolipin-biosynthetic gene cluster. A halogenase has been postulated to be responsible for attaching chlorine to the PKS-precursor of lysolipin. In a PCR screening of S. tendae Tü 4042 with primers speciﬁc for halogenase genes, a 260- bp DNA fragment was ampliﬁed. In total, 2304 clones were screened with both DIG-labeled probes. On the arrayed hybridization ﬁlter, 13 clones were hybridized with the KSα-probe and 11 with the halogenase probe. Three cosmids (4H04, 4O22, and 3J01) that cohybridized with both probes (KS+/Halo+) were selected for further analysis. 3.2. Heterologous expression of the lysolipin-biosynthetic gene cluster

The three KS+/Halo+ cosmids were transferred to S. albus by triparental intergeneric conjugation. Recombinant S. albus exconju- gants were isolated after apramycin selection. Resistant colonies were tested for lysolipin production. Of the three tested cosmids, 4H04, was able to confer lysolipin production to S. albus. HPLC analysis clearly indicated the biosynthesis of two new substances by the S. albus strain expressing the putative lysolipin-biosynthetic genes. These sub- stances were further analyzed by mass spectrometry. In acidiﬁed extracts of clones carrying cosmid 4H04, a substance with m/z = 598 [M + H]+ was detected, corresponding to lysolipin I (Fig. 2). The mass spectrum displayed the typical isotopic pattern of a singly chlorinated substance, and the UV/Vis spectra matched the standard and a reference spectrum for lysolipin I in a UV/Vis spectral library (Fiedler, P. Lopez et al. / Gene 461 (2010) 5–14 1993). This result indicated that the substance produced in the recombinant S. albus 4H04 is lysolipin I. The presence of lysolipin I in the culture supernatant of the heterologous host demonstrated that cosmid 4H04 contains all of the genes required for lysolipin production in S. albus. Nevertheless, the possible involvement of enzymes encoded in PKS clusters found in the S. albus chromosome cannot be fully excluded.

The heterologous expression of the aromatic polyketide actinor- hodin was ﬁrst reported in 1984 (Malpartida and Hopwood, 1984). Recently, this method has become very important in biosynthetic investigations (Fujii, 2009). Heterologous expression has been successful for other aromatic polyketide biosynthesis clusters, such as R1128 (Marti et al., 2000), griseorhodin (Li and Piel, 2002), resistomycin (Jakobi and Hertweck, 2004), chartreusin (Xu et al., 2005), fredericamycin (Wendt-Pienkowski et al., 2005), benastatin (Xu et al., 2007), CBS40 (Hornung et al., 2007) and alnumycin (Oja et al., 2008). In the case of stefﬁmycin, an accessory expression of rhamnose-biosynthesis genes was required to produce the antibiotic in a heterologous host (Gullon et al., 2006). There have also been reports of successful expression of cryptic gene clusters in heterol- ogous hosts (e.g. Palmu et al., 2007). 3.3. The lysolipin-biosynthetic gene cluster Cosmid (4H04) conferring lysolipin production in the heterolo- gous host was shotgun-sequenced, assembled using phred/phrap/ consed (Ewing et al., 1998; Ewing and Green, 1998; Gordon et al., 1998) and semiautomatically annotated. The results obtained by the annotation software were subjected to manual editing and approval. In total, 46 open reading frames (ORFs) were identiﬁed in the 43.2- kb cosmid insert, with an average GC content of 72.3%. According to the results of the annotation pipeline, 44 out of 46 ORFs encoded on the cosmid insert were assigned to the lysolipin cluster and named “llp” genes (Fig. 3 and Table 1). 3.4. Formation of the lysolipin polyketide backbone

it was postulated by Bockholt et al., that malonamyl-CoA may be used as a starter unit. This hypothesis was based on isotope feeding studies using labeled malonic acid, which indicated that all three carbon atoms of malonate are incorporated into the lysolipin carbon skeleton (Bockholt et al., 1994). In the lysolipin gene cluster, the gene llpA encodes a putative amidotransferase with high similarity to asparagine synthetases that are involved in the primary metabolism of non-actinomycete strains (40% identity to B. subtilis AsnO; Swissprot: O05272). Asparagine synthetases transfer a glutamine-derived amino group to aspartate, forming asparagine (Boehlein et al., 1996). Thus, it can be speculated that, in a similar reaction, an amino group from glutamine might be transferred to malonic acid or malonyl-CoA, resulting in a malona- mide or malonamyl-CoA, respectively. Interestingly, malonamyl-CoA has also been proposed to be a starter unit in oxytetracycline biosynthesis. It has been shown experimentally that the amidotrans- ferase OxyD, a homologue of LlpA (54% amino acid identity), is necessary and sufﬁcient to produce amidated polyketide precursors (Zhang et al., 2006). Another example of a similar starting mechanism was postulated for cervimycin biosynthesis (Herold et al., 2004). Nevertheless, the possibility that the substrate for LlpA is a polyketide intermediate and not malonyl-CoA cannot be completely excluded. Similar amidotransferases have also been identiﬁed in other biosynthetic gene clusters that encode the proteins involved in the biosynthesis of substances with N-heterocycles, where malonamyl- CoA cannot function as a starter unit. As the amidation occurs on a longer acyl chain, it is postulated that FdmV acts on a noncyclized fredericamycin precursor molecule. Moreover, the pradimicin gene cluster also contains a gene, pdmN, which is homologous to llpA. Its gene product, PdmN, has been shown to be responsible for attaching D-alanine or D-serine to the pradimicin polyketide precursor (Zhan et al., 2009).

Interestingly, the griseorhodin and rubromycin biosynthesis gene clusters, whose products are structurally related to lysolipin but do not contain nitrogen heterocycles, also contain amidotransferase-like genes (grhP and rubR). In both pathways these enzymes are thought to be inactive due to a Cys→Ser amino acid exchange in a highly conserved region (van Heeke and Schuster, 1989). Similar to most other aromatic polyketide gene clusters, the three genes (llpF (KSα), llpE (KSβ), and llpD (ACP)) encoding the minimal PKS enzymes are colocalized. The KSα subunit, encoded by llpF, has condensation motifs similar to PKS and FAS (Dreier and Khosla, 2000). The acyl carrier protein LlpD contains the conserved LGYDSLA (Lambalot et al., 1996; Schlumbohm et al., 1991) motif typical for ACP. The loading of malonate extender units requires the activity of a malonyl- CoA:ACP transacylase (MCAT). No MCAT-encoding genes were found in the lysolipin cluster. Thus, it was assumed that the MCAT function is either recruited from primary metabolism (Summers et al., 1995) or is an intrinsic property of the ACP LlpD, as is the case for the actinorhodin ACP in S. coelicolor (Arthur et al., 2005, 2006). An ORF analysis based on Zcurve (Guo et al., 2003) and manual comparisons with known genes of other clusters revealed that all three genes encoding the minimal PKS (KSα: llpF, KSβ: llpE, ACP: llpD) overlap at their start and stop codons by four nucleotides (Fig. S1, supplementary material). Overlapping start/stop codons are common for KSα/KSβ-encoding genes, but an overlap of KSβ- and ACP-encoding genes is very uncommon. Interestingly, llpD, which encodes the ACP, has a TTG start codon. Although TTG has never been observed as the start codon of ACPs in the antibiotic-biosynthesis gene clusters characterized to date, this codon is not uncommon in streptomycetes.

In lysolipin biosynthesis, the tight gene arrangement of over- lapping start/stop codons in the minimal PKS area is extended to the upstream region of llpF where the cyclase genes, llpCII and llpCIII, are encoded. llpCII also overlaps with the start codon of the KSα-encoding gene, is encoded directly downstream of the ACP gene llpD and is only separated by two nucleotides. It can be assumed that this complex is cotranscribed and probably translationally coupled. Three putative cyclase-encoding genes, llpCI, llpCII, and llpCIII, are present in the lysolipin cluster. Cyclases are essential for cyclizing the highly unstable open polyketide chain formed by the minimal PKS (e.g. Ames et al., 2008; Fritzsche et al., 2008; Meurer and Hutchinson, 1995).

LlpCI (155 aa) displays high similarity to the cyclase domain of the bifunctional cyclases/3-oxoacyl-ACP reductases GrhT (62% amino acid identity within 150 aa) and RubF (62% identity within 150 aa) of the griseorhodin and rubromycin clusters, respectively, and to the monofunctional cyclase PdmD (59% identity) involved in pradimicin biosynthesis. Coexpression of PdmD with the pradimicin minimal PKS (PdmABC) leads to polyketide intermediates with a closed B ring (Zhan et al., 2008), providing a strong hint that LlpCI may analogously catalyze B-ring cyclization between C-8 and C-9 in lysolipin biosynthesis. Sequence similarities of LlpCII (142 aa) to known enzymes such as TcmJ (50% amino acid identity) imply that LlpCII is also involved in the formation of the correct polyketide backbone. LlpCIII (111 aa), the smallest cyclase in the lysolipin cluster, shows similarities to the cyclases RubE/GrhQ (68% amino acid identity). Phylogenetic analyses of cyclases (Fritzsche et al., 2008) indicate that this enzyme is a member of a cyclase clade putatively involved in the cyclizations of rings D and/or E. 3.5. Redox modiﬁcations of the backbone The primary product in lysolipin biosynthesis is lysolipin X, which contains twelve oxygens. According to studies with isotopically labeled precursors, nine of these oxygens are derived from molecular oxygen (Fig. 1) and do not originate from PKS biosynthesis (Bockholt et al., 1994). In total, 16 enzymes, which are probably involved in redox reactions, were identiﬁed.

Based on isotope-feeding experiments by Bockholt et al. (1994), multiple reduction steps of the polyketide precursor are postulated. These reductions are most likely performed by four reductases, LlpZI– LlpZIV; LlpZI, LlpZIII, and LlpZIV have similarities to putative 3-oxoacyl- ACP-reductases (for similarities, see Table 1). LlpZI is similar to BenL (58% amino acid identity), which has been shown to be involved in the reduction of C-19 of benastatin and thus may act on the corresponding position C-15 in lysolipin (Lackner et al., 2007). LlpOII and LlpOIII are similar to monooxygenases identiﬁed in the rubromycin, griseorhodin, and pradimicin gene clusters (Table 1). They contain motifs previously identiﬁed in ActVA-ORF6, a mono- oxygenase involved in the oxidation of an aromatic anthrone- intermediate to the corresponding quinone in actinorhodin biosyn- thesis (Sciara et al., 2003). LlpOIII is highly similar to PdmH (60% identity), which catalyzes the formation of the quinone moiety of the pradimicin B ring (Zhan et al., 2008). Therefore, LlpOIII may be involved in a similar reaction at C-10 position (ring B) of the lysolipin structure. Three putative cytochrome-P450-dependent monooxygenases were identiﬁed (LlpOIV, LlpOVI, and LlpOVII) within the lysolipin gene cluster. From sequence similarities alone, it is not possible to speculate where the individual oxygenases may act on the lysolipin structure. One of them may be involved in the formation of the methylenedioxy bridge, resulting in ring G. In plants, similar mechanisms have been described in the biosynthesis of stylopine (Bauer and Zenk, 1991; llpF. The third cyclase gene, P. Lopez et al. / Gene 461 (2010) 5–14

Ikezawa et al., 2007), berberine (Ikezawa et al., 2003; Rueffer and Zenk, 1994), maackiain (Clemens and Barz, 1996) and, (+)-sesamin (Ono et al., 2006). In these cases, a P450 oxygenase joins adjacent hydroxy and methoxy moieties. The hypothesis that the ﬁrst hydroxy group is methylated and is then subject to methylenedioxy-bridge formation is supported by evidence that the C-29 atom is derived from S-adenosyl-methionine (Bockholt et al., 1994). A [3Fe-4S]-ferredoxin encoding gene, llpK, which may act as an electron donor for the P450 oxygenases, was identiﬁed as being directly downstream of the P450- monooxygenase gene llpOIV. Bockholt et al. suggested that a Baeyer–Villiger-oxidation is necessary for the synthesis of the xanthone structure. Although there are three FAD-dependent oxygenases (LlpOI, LlpOV, and LlpOVIII) present in the cluster, none have the FXGX3HX3(Y/F) (Fraaije et al., 2002) motif that is typical of Baeyer–Villiger monooxygenases. Rearrangements of the polyphenolic polyketide backbone are also known to occur in the biosyntheses of other pradimicin-type antibiotics. Spiroketal carbons are generated in the biosynthesis of In griseorhodin (Li and Piel, 2002; Yunt et al., 2009) and fredericamycin (Chen et al., 2008a; Wendt-Pienkowski et al., 2005). As in the hypothetical xanthone-formation pathway in lysolipin biosynthesis (Bockholt et al., 1994), these reactions also include the elimination of single carbons from the polyketide chain.

Three additional genes play unidentiﬁed roles in the oxidative modiﬁcation of the lysolipin precursor: LlpS is a protein with similarity to 3-hydroxyisobutyrate dehydrogenases, LlpU is a member of the “short-chain dehydrogenase/reductase” family, and LlpL is a putative NAD(P)-dependent hydroxylase with similarity to SnoaW (34% amino acid identity). 3.6. Other tailoring reactions Lysolipin is methylated at ﬁve positions. Isotope-labeling studies have indicated that these ﬁve methyl groups are derived from S- adenosyl-methionine (Bockholt et al., 1994). Surprisingly, the lysolipin cluster contains six putative genes encoding methyl transferases, named llpMI to llpMVI. Their deduced gene products contain conserved SAM-binding domains and show similarities to O- methyltransferases from different antibiotic-biosynthesis pathways (for similarities, see Table 1). Additional experimental evidence will be required to assign site speciﬁcity to the individual methyltrans- ferases and to determine why six methyltransferase genes are present in the cluster while only ﬁve methylations seem to be needed for lysolipin biosynthesis. The protein sequence of the putative lysolipin-halogenase LlpH, shows high similarity to other pyrrole/phenol-speciﬁc ﬂavin-depen- dent halogenases of actinomycetes, including BhaA (36% amino acid identity, 58% amino acid similarity), which is involved in the biosynthesis of the chlorinated glycopeptide antibiotic balhimycin (Puk et al., 2002). Because lysolipin is only halogenated at one position, it can be assumed that LlpH chlorinates lysolipin at the C-1 position. 3.7. Transport and regulation

is S. albus, the host strain used for heterologous expression, sensitive to lysolipin. When this strain was transformed with the cosmid 4H04 containing the lysolipin-biosynthetic genes, it not only produced lysolipin in amounts comparable to wild-type S. tendae but also exhibited resistance to the antibiotic. This result indicates that at least 1 of the 46 identiﬁed genes of the lysolipin biosynthetic gene cluster is responsible for this phenotype. One candidate for conveying resistance is LlpN, which shows high similarity to a putative antibiotic-resistance-related transport protein from Corynebacterium diphtheriae and to other membrane transporters from the streptomycetes. Five putative regulators, encoded by llpRI to llpRV, are present in the lysolipin-biosynthetic gene cluster. LlpRI shows similarity to BPSL3380, a PadR-like protein (47% amino acid identity) from Burkholderia. Protein-domain analysis for LlpRII and LlpRIII revealed motifs from TENA/THI-regulators in the thiazole biosynthetic operon in B. subtilis. LlpRIV is a member of the “Streptomyces antibiotic regulatory protein” (SARP) family (Wietzorrek and Bibb, 1997). LlpRIV is similar to FdmR (43% amino acid identity), which has been experimentally shown to be a positive regulator in fredericamycin biosynthesis (Chen et al., 2008b). The HTH-motif containing LlpRV has high similarity (75% amino acid identity) to putative DNA-binding proteins (SCO7706) from S. coelicolor A3(2). 3.8. Genes with unknown functions

With llpG, the lysolipin cluster unexpectedly contained a gene encoding a glycosyltransferase. No glycosylated lysolipins or lysolipin derivatives have been isolated from S. tendae Tü 4042. It is hypothesized that this enzyme may be inactive and unnecessary for lysolipin synthesis. Other structurally related metabolites, such as IB-00208 (Rodriguez et al., 2003) and kigamicin (Kunimoto et al., 2003), have been shown to be glycosylated. While a glycosyltransferase may have been included in the ancestral biosynthesis pathway, it likely became obsolete during the evolution of lysolipin biosynthesis. Another possibility is that this gene could be involved in resistance formation, as glycosyltransferases are known to mediate resistance against some macrolides (Jenkins and Cundliffe, 1991). To test this hypothesis, the gene was cloned into the integrative vector pRM4.3 (Menges et al., 2007) under control of the constitutive ermE* promoter and introduced into S. albus which is sensitive for lysolipin. 1 × 108 spores of S. albus were embedded in soft agar and ﬁlter discs containing 1 or 10 µg lysolipin were put on the plates. No signiﬁcant difference of the diameter of the inhibition zones was observed in S. albus strains expressing llpG and a control strain carrying the empty vector pRM4.3 (Fig. S2, supplementary material). This shows that llpG is not directly involved in lysolipin resistance and its role in lysolipin biosynthesis remains open.

The putative function of seven genes from the lysolipin cluster could not be predicted clearly from homology analysis. Two gene products, LlpT and LlpV, are very similar to each other in size and amino acid sequence. They show high similarity to the core region of CurD from the curamycin biosynthesis gene cluster (Bergh and Uhlen, 1992) and to WhiE-ORF1 from the S. coelicolor WhiE cluster. The roles and functions of CurD and WhiE-ORF1 are unknown. LlpB and LlpQ are similar to FdmM, RubQ, GrhM, and Pms5 (ORF5), which were all identiﬁed in other pradimicin-type biosynthesis clusters. No function has been experimentally determined for these proteins. 3.9. Analysis of the border regions of the gene cluster A partial orf (orf46) is located upstream of the methyl transferase gene llpMVI that encodes a protein fragment very similar to terminal proteins of other Streptomyces species. These proteins bind to the terminal inverted repeats at the 5′ ends of the linear Streptomyces chromosomes or plasmids and ensure stable replication. In S. coelicolor, the corresponding gene, tpgC, is located approximately 100 kb from the right end of the linear chromosome (Yang et al., 2002). The same situation can be seen in S. avermitilis, where tpgA is one of the outermost genes in the chromosome. The presence of orf46 next to lysolipin-biosynthetic genes suggests that the gene cluster may also be located near the end of the chromosome. As the loss of DNA fragments and homologous recombinations are frequently observed toward the outer parts of the chromosome (Volff and Altenbuchner, 1998), the terminal localization of the gene cluster could be an explanation for the frequent loss of lysolipin production ability in S. tendae and S. violaceoniger Tü 96 (Fiedler, personal P. Lopez et al. / Gene 461 (2010) 5–14

communication). The pivotal role of terminal proteins in replication strongly suggests that orf46 is not involved in lysolipin biosynthesis and thus marks one end of the biosynthesis gene cluster. orf1 is the ﬁrst gene on the upstream side of the cosmid insert. The encoded protein is very similar (59% amino acid identity) to a conserved hypothetical protein with no known function from Streptomyces coelicolor A3(2) (CAC44563.1). We cannot deﬁnitively say whether orf1 is required for biosynthesis. The polyketide lysolipin is highly active against gram-positive pathogens. However, its high cytotoxicity toward eukaryotic cells presents a large barrier for the clinical use of this compound. Genetic engineering is a promising approach to overcome this limitation because it allows for directed optimization of the molecule. Here, we reported the identiﬁcation, isolation and heterologous expression of the lysolipin-biosynthetic gene cluster of S. tendae Tü 4042 and demonstrated its completeness. The sequence analysis, which allowed the deduction of a hypothetical biosynthetic pathway (Fig. 1), is an important contribution to a better understanding of the biosynthesis of complex aromatic polyketides because of its unique structure, unprecedented complement of post-PKS reductions and oxygenations, and high number of genes encoding enzymes involved in tailoring processes. These data are basic requirements for targeted manipulations of the pathway to generate novel derivatives that might overcome the toxicity observed for wild-type lysolipin.
